Dallas Leslie "Digger" Royall was born in July 1949, his father was a guitarist.

In 1969 he joined Reeb Revol in Melbourne on drums alongside Ian "Gunther" Gorman on guitar, Graham Patrick on saxophone, Paul Reynolds on bass guitar and vocals, Ron Shepherd on vocals and Peter Smith on trumpet.

In January 1973 he joined a pop rock group, McAskill, on drums, which were formed in Sydney by Barrie "The Bear" McAskill on vocals, Michael Barnes on guitar, Steve Doran on organ and Doug Stirling on bass guitar.
Also in 1973 Royall was briefly the drummer for Melbourne-based blues rockers, Band of Talabene.
In July 1975 he joined hard rock group, Buster Brown, alongside Angry Anderson on lead vocals, Ken Firth on bass guitar (ex-Tully), Billy Miller on guitar and vocals, and Dave Springfield on guitar.
Royall and Anderson relocated to Sydney and joined fellow hard rockers, Rose Tattoo, in 1976.
He was recorded on their first three studio albums, Rose Tattoo (October 1978), Assault & Battery (September 1981) and Scarred for Life (October 1982).

Dallas Leslie "Digger" Royall (1949 – 1991) was an Australian hard rock drummer.
According to Rose Tattoo's official website's biography, from October 1982, "[he is] a former Army chopper pilot who's spent the past fifteen years thrashing the kit & the bottle."
In the following year he was a member of Salty Dog with Gorman on guitar and vocals, Les Catterall on lead vocals, Scotty Ingram on guitar and vocals and Chris Willing on bass guitar.
In July 1975 he joined hard rock group, Buster Brown, alongside Angry Anderson on lead vocals, Ken Firth on bass guitar (ex-Tully), Billy Miller on guitar and vocals, and Dave Springfield on guitar.
Buster Brown disbanded in November of that year, when Firth, Miller and Springfield became members of The Ferrets.
Royall was also credited as co-composer for much of the group's first album including the early singles, "Rock 'n' Roll Outlaw" (September 1978) and "One of the Boys" (November).
